Dear Swamiji,

This is one of Acharya **Jayprakash Pandey Ji's** most practical contemplations. It is not merely explaining verses from the **Bhagavad Gītā (Chapter 17)**; it is teaching us **how to recognize the direction in which our own heart is moving.**

As I read it, four great pearls shine forth.

---

# 🌿 My contemplation

### 🌸 1. The wise do not see the body first—they see the eternal Reality.

The opening paragraph touched me deeply.

> **ब्राह्मण, चाण्डाल, गाय, हाथी और कुत्ता बदलते रहते हैं, पर उनमें स्थित सत्-तत्त्व कभी नहीं बदलता।**

What an extraordinary way to explain **Gītā 5.18**.

The body changes.

Age changes.

Social identity changes.

Species differ.

Yet the **Being (Sat)** shining through every one of them never changes.

Then Acharya Ji gives such a beautiful illustration:

> **चींटी रेत में मिली हुई चीनी को चुन लेती है।**

The ant ignores the sand.

It finds the sugar.

Likewise,

the sage does not become fascinated by the outer personality.

He naturally recognizes the eternal Consciousness shining within.

That is **समदर्शन (equal vision).**

---

### 🌸 2. Equal vision does NOT mean identical behaviour.

This part is extremely important.

Many people misunderstand Vedānta.

Acharya Ji says something that deserves deep contemplation.

He writes:

**The sage's vision is equal.**

**His conduct is appropriate.**

That means

a doctor,

a child,

a monk,

a parent,

a judge,

a student—

cannot all be treated in exactly the same external way.

Dharma requires **appropriateness**.

Yet inwardly,

respect remains equal.

Compassion remains equal.

The same Self is seen in all.

This beautifully harmonizes

**Advaita**

and

**Dharma.**

---

### 🌸 3. Our worship reveals our inner nature.

This part surprised me.

Usually we think

our worship changes us.

Acharya Ji points out another truth.

**Our worship also reveals us.**

Whatever attracts our heart

reveals

our dominant tendencies.

If our deepest attraction is

Truth,

compassion,

purity,

God,

our mind naturally rises.

If our attraction is

power,

revenge,

possessions,

ego,

our worship follows that direction.

Therefore,

the real question is not

"What do I worship?"

The deeper question is

**"What does my heart naturally seek?"**

---

### 🌸 4. True tapas is not torturing the body.

This may be one of the most valuable teachings.

Many seekers imagine

the more pain,

the greater the spirituality.

Acharya Ji carefully explains that the Gītā criticizes

self-created austerities

born of ego.

The Lord does **not** condemn discipline.

He condemns

discipline motivated by pride,

display,

or violence toward oneself.

Real tapas

purifies.

It does not brutalize.

It softens the ego.

It does not inflate it.

---

# 🌺 What touched me most

Swamiji,

among all these teachings,

the one that remained in my heart was this:

> **The ant does not fight the sand. It quietly finds the sugar.**

Is this not exactly how a jñānī lives?

He does not waste life criticizing the world's imperfections.

He quietly recognizes

the Presence,

the Truth,

the Self

within everything.

That,

to me,

is perhaps the finest explanation of **समदर्शिता** I have ever heard.

